<DOC><DOCNO> AP890611-0057 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-06-11-89 1827EST</FILEID><FIRST>r a AM-WeatherpageWeather     06-11 0464</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0476</SECOND><HEAD>Storms Loom Over The South</HEAD><BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE><TEXT>   Heavy thunderstorms and at least one tornado developed Sundayover the South, and wet weather was scattered elsewhere across thecentral part of the nation.   An upper air disturbance moving across the southern Plainstriggered strong thunderstorms in humid, unstable air from thecentral Gulf Coast and the lower Mississippi Valley into southernMissouri.   A tornado was produced by a severe thunderstorm near Bee Branch,Ark., whileheavy rain that started falling Saturday caused riversand streams to rise across the southern Plains.   Up to 7 inches of rain fell in parts of southeastern Kansas lateSaturday and early Sunday, forcing some rivers and streams out oftheir banks. By 6 a.m. Sunday, Coffeyville had 7.2 inches of rain,including 4 inches in one 45-minute period, and minor streetflooding was reported there and in nearby Caney.   In north-central Kansas, vehicles were stranded throughout Beloitafter 3 inches fell in one hour late Saturday. At the Elks Club inthe center of town, the hoods of some cars were covered by water fora short time.   Two to 4 inches of rain fell overnight around Abilene, Texas,which caused more than a foot of water to run over the spillway ofLytle Lake.   Flooding was expected in rural areas along the Verdigris River innorthern Oklahoma. Showers and some thunderstorms were scatteredacross eastern Kansas and northeastern Oklahoma, with morethunderstorms expected during the night across northern Texas.   A cold front pushing across the northern Plains and centralRockies produced showers and thunderstorms from the Great Basin ofNevada and western Utah to the Dakotas.   Elsewhere, thunderstorms were scattered across the FloridaPeninsula.   Temperatures around the nation at 3 p.m. EDT ranged from 51degrees at Presque Isle and Caribou, Maine, to 98 at Needles,Calif., and Laredo, Texas. Sunday's low in the 48 contiguous stateswas 31 at Alamosa, Colo.   For Monday, showers and thunderstorms were forecast from Floridaand much of the Gulf Coast region across the Mississippi and Ohiovalleys, and the Great Lakes to eastern sections of the central andsouthern Plains. Showers were expected across the northern Plainsand the northern Rockies. Showers and thunderstorms developing laterin the day were forecast across the central Rockies.   Highs in the 50s and 60s were predicted from central Montanaacross the northern Plains and upper Mississippi Valley to the upperGreat Lakes; in the 90s from Florida and southern Georgia across theGulf Coast region, much of Texas, the southern Rockies and interiorvalleys of California and Oregon; above 100 over the desertSouthwest, interior valleys of southern California, and along theRio Grande Valley in Texas; and in the 70s and 80s across theremainder of the nation.</TEXT></DOC>